WEBVTT

00:02.953 --> 00:07.756
♪ ♪

00:07.858 --> 00:09.925
WILL SMITH: The sun...

00:10.461 --> 00:13.362
Gives us warmth and light.

00:14.765 --> 00:17.399
It is the fuel of life.

00:17.868 --> 00:22.771
Without the energy of the
sun almost nothing grows,
thrives or lives.

00:25.543 --> 00:29.611
But the sun was not
put there for our benefit.

00:29.847 --> 00:35.317
It is not this big jolly ball
of nice smiling down on us,
wishing us all a good day.

00:36.587 --> 00:38.921
It is not our friend.

00:39.023 --> 00:41.924
The sun is a monster.

00:43.627 --> 00:46.295
A planet killer.

00:48.933 --> 00:52.434
And we don't see that
side of the sun down here.

00:53.571 --> 00:58.841
But eight astronauts,
with over 1,000 days in
space between them,

00:58.943 --> 01:05.314
Can show us how being up there
helped them understand the
suns bright fury.

01:11.455 --> 01:13.422
JEFF: It's got an incredible
amount of power which you

01:13.524 --> 01:15.991
really appreciate when
you go out in space.

01:16.827 --> 01:20.796
MAE: Just like the
gods of old, the sun
can give life and it

01:20.898 --> 01:23.465
can destroy life.

01:25.269 --> 01:26.869
JERRY: It's a
mean son of a gun.

01:26.971 --> 01:30.672
It's exploding and it's
sending cosmic radiation at us.

01:32.643 --> 01:35.844
-Given the amount of radiation
from the sun, there shouldn't

01:35.946 --> 01:38.180
be life on the
surface of the earth.

01:39.216 --> 01:42.484
We shouldn't be here.

01:46.323 --> 01:47.823
WILL SMITH: But we are here.

01:47.925 --> 01:51.226
And we owe our
lives to this world.

01:51.729 --> 01:54.997
I'm gonna tell you
how the earths core...

01:55.833 --> 01:58.100
The air above us....

01:58.202 --> 02:02.638
and life itself
work to protect us.

02:04.041 --> 02:08.977
The earth shields us
in a suit of armor.

02:09.947 --> 02:13.081
And the way she does it...

02:15.986 --> 02:19.388
Is one hell of
a strange story.

02:35.606 --> 02:38.540
(car horn)

02:45.115 --> 02:49.484
♪ ♪

02:49.587 --> 02:51.720
You see that guy in the crowd?

02:51.822 --> 02:54.790
He's just a bit different
from the rest of us.

02:57.595 --> 02:59.761
He's a spaceman.

03:01.131 --> 03:07.436
Once he risked his
life to fix a telescope
350 miles above the earth.

03:10.908 --> 03:14.643
And he's spent a lifetime
studying the stars.

03:17.381 --> 03:19.982
-People still feel this
incredible fascination with,

03:20.084 --> 03:23.819
with looking at the sun.

03:31.295 --> 03:36.231
Twice a year it just
crosses the line of the
cross streets of Manhattan...

03:38.836 --> 03:42.304
And sets at just that right
point that it just makes a

03:42.406 --> 03:46.475
beautiful orange glow
which permeates the city.

03:47.645 --> 03:51.546
In some sense I suppose I
could say I saw more of the

03:51.649 --> 03:54.883
true character of the sun...

03:54.985 --> 03:58.220
Than people who are always
on the surface of the earth.

04:03.160 --> 04:08.163
You open the airlock and
then turn around and look up.

04:13.203 --> 04:15.904
It's like that great scene in
the Wizard of Oz where Dorothy

04:16.006 --> 04:18.707
comes out of the
house and it's not
black and white anymore.

04:19.710 --> 04:23.011
All of a sudden, the
whole world is in color.

04:24.648 --> 04:26.782
<i>WOMAN (over radio): But</i>
<i>don't forget those visors.</i>

04:26.884 --> 04:30.319
<i>They do come in</i>
<i>handy when that big fire</i>
<i>ball is staring at you.</i>

04:30.988 --> 04:32.688
-Yep.

04:36.694 --> 04:41.096
One of my great eureka
moments was realizing for
the first time when I

04:41.198 --> 04:44.066
was in space that
I was seeing the sun
in a black sky.

04:44.535 --> 04:47.536
Think of that.

04:48.672 --> 04:52.374
You really see
the sun as a star.

04:56.547 --> 04:59.414
Particularly when I
was out in the space suit,

04:59.516 --> 05:02.417
the power of the sun
just hits you in the guts.

05:04.188 --> 05:07.022
It just goes through
your entire body.

05:09.026 --> 05:12.594
LELAND: The temperature
extremes are 250 degrees in

05:12.696 --> 05:15.964
the sun and then minus
250 in the shade.

05:16.066 --> 05:21.103
That's pretty incredible
and that our suits can
withstand those temperatures.

05:28.579 --> 05:32.781
-But even we astronauts
only experience a fraction
of the sun's power.

05:40.691 --> 05:43.558
It has many weapons
it can send our way.

05:45.462 --> 05:50.065
Heat, light and
deadly flares that can
devastate entire planets.

05:52.336 --> 05:54.903
Look at Mars.

05:57.808 --> 06:00.976
Billions of years ago we
think it was just like us...

06:04.748 --> 06:08.417
A potential cradle for life.

06:09.319 --> 06:13.021
But radiation from
the sun ravaged it.

06:15.259 --> 06:18.760
Solar flares with the
destructive power of billions

06:18.862 --> 06:23.665
of Hiroshima atomic
bombs helped chew
away Mars's atmosphere

06:29.273 --> 06:33.008
and the oceans
evaporated into space.

06:46.256 --> 06:50.025
WILL SMITH: Earth is even
closer to the sun than Mars,

06:51.028 --> 06:53.762
so how come we're
not dust and ashes?

06:53.864 --> 06:57.866
See, the thing is, our
planet is strong on defense.

07:01.371 --> 07:04.039
And every player has a role.

07:06.710 --> 07:09.644
From the edge of space...

07:12.950 --> 07:15.484
To the deepest oceans...

07:18.655 --> 07:21.523
To one of the most
hostile places on earth.

07:36.473 --> 07:38.507
SIMS: We'll be sleeping
with gas masks on.

07:39.343 --> 07:41.309
Sometimes it'll clear up and
be beautiful but most of the

07:41.411 --> 07:43.545
time we'll be wearing our
gas masks even to bed.

07:45.883 --> 07:48.917
WILL SMITH: Ken Sims
doesn't do nine to five.

07:58.061 --> 08:01.563
This is his idea of a
good day at the office.

08:04.501 --> 08:07.969
For over 20 years he's
ventured into active volcanoes

08:08.071 --> 08:11.573
across the globe to collect
samples of molten lava.

08:14.111 --> 08:17.279
Studying this stuff is one of
the best ways to understand

08:17.381 --> 08:21.349
what's happening in the center
of the earth and the process

08:21.451 --> 08:23.785
that protects us from the sun.

08:27.124 --> 08:30.926
KANE: Pretty much that
whole bottom terrace now is
completely covered in brand new

08:31.028 --> 08:32.928
lava flow, isn't it?

08:33.030 --> 08:36.298
-Yeah. And with the new
lava flow coming around
against the wall there,

08:36.400 --> 08:39.401
we'll have to watch out.

08:39.903 --> 08:44.139
The lava's intensely hot,
roughly 2,000 degrees.

08:46.076 --> 08:48.910
It will burn pretty much
anything on contact.

08:56.753 --> 08:59.287
-Okay, heading over.

09:08.966 --> 09:10.732
I'll go over just
towards the edge here.

09:10.834 --> 09:13.435
We'll have a look.

09:21.712 --> 09:24.045
Whoa.

09:31.855 --> 09:34.589
Holy...

09:38.895 --> 09:41.329
It's just opened up on
that side, hasn't it?

09:41.431 --> 09:44.633
-Yeah, totally.
-Whoa.

09:44.735 --> 09:49.404
Yeah, Ken, I'm pretty certain
that there is absolutely no
way we are going down there.

09:49.506 --> 09:53.208
That is without doubt
mission impossible.

09:57.547 --> 10:00.081
-Okay, well, we're
cancelling this mission.

10:00.417 --> 10:01.850
-Yeah.

10:01.952 --> 10:04.919
-Just anybody with half a
brain wouldn't go down there.

10:07.557 --> 10:10.892
WILL SMITH: The new
vent means Ken can't
take samples from the lake,

10:12.329 --> 10:14.396
but he doesn't need to.

10:14.498 --> 10:17.932
The vent is firing
fresh lava right at him.

10:26.009 --> 10:28.176
-There's a lot of lava
bombs around here.

10:28.278 --> 10:30.879
It's just covered with bombs.

10:35.018 --> 10:36.117
Wow, I'm...

10:36.219 --> 10:38.119
can see the vent from here.

10:38.221 --> 10:40.288
It's really rocking
and rolling.

10:40.390 --> 10:44.859
-I'm gonna head back up, over.
-Sure, I'll come back.

10:53.870 --> 10:57.672
The solid lava samples we've
collected are radioactive.

10:57.774 --> 11:01.376
They have uranium
and thorium in them.

11:03.447 --> 11:07.782
Those elements are really
important for maintaining the
heat of the earth.

11:19.796 --> 11:21.496
WILL SMITH: But wait a second.

11:21.598 --> 11:26.000
What does any of this
have to do with keeping
us safe from the sun?

11:29.606 --> 11:33.908
Radioactive lava up here
proves there's a raging

11:34.010 --> 11:37.545
nuclear furnace at the
heart of our planet.

11:41.985 --> 11:46.221
It is one big ball
of incredible heat.

11:46.323 --> 11:49.591
I mean, a very big ball.

11:54.664 --> 11:56.698
But that's not all.

11:56.800 --> 12:00.668
These molten insides are
full of iron and nickel.

12:05.776 --> 12:10.311
Rising, falling, spinning in
a constantly melting furnace.

12:13.984 --> 12:18.787
And all that churning metal
creates its own magnetic field.

12:28.532 --> 12:33.001
♪ ♪

12:33.537 --> 12:39.974
This magnetic field
stretches as far as
400,000 miles into space...

12:43.213 --> 12:47.182
surrounding the entire planet.

12:49.119 --> 12:53.621
It is a massive force field
and it helps deflect the

12:53.723 --> 12:59.294
deadly radiation
that destroyed Mars.

13:09.005 --> 13:11.973
♪ ♪

13:12.075 --> 13:16.377
-For the most part our
magnetic field is invisible.

13:18.215 --> 13:22.417
But when the sun flares up,
we get to see it in action.

13:23.820 --> 13:26.454
We call it the aurora.

13:26.556 --> 13:31.092
It's pretty much on
everyone's bucket list
but in space you see it in an

13:31.194 --> 13:33.862
entirely different way.

13:39.703 --> 13:41.903
LELAND: I saw this green glow.

13:42.005 --> 13:44.873
It's almost like
a person dancing.

13:44.975 --> 13:49.777
It was a shape and
these forms that were
moving as we went over.

13:53.717 --> 13:57.852
CHRIS: And the greens and reds
and all of the faint colors,

13:57.954 --> 14:01.356
like this enormous
ghost of a curtain.

14:05.695 --> 14:08.530
NICOLE: You're not just
seeing it with your eyes.

14:08.632 --> 14:10.331
It, you're feeling it.

14:10.433 --> 14:12.534
You're feeling it with
your heart as well.

14:12.636 --> 14:16.271
It's a part of you.

14:21.811 --> 14:24.612
-When we look down at the
aurora it's all the more

14:24.714 --> 14:28.049
beautiful because
we know that we're
looking at our planet

14:28.151 --> 14:32.053
keeping us safe from the sun.

14:35.825 --> 14:37.992
WILL SMITH: But you know what?

14:38.094 --> 14:41.696
It takes more than that one
shield to keep us alive...

14:44.501 --> 14:47.435
because the sun
has another weapon.

14:47.537 --> 14:49.837
A silent assassin.

14:49.940 --> 14:52.006
The assassin's name?

14:52.108 --> 14:53.741
Light.

15:00.487 --> 15:03.188
WILL SMITH: Everything
revolves around the sun.

15:03.290 --> 15:05.657
Literally.

15:05.759 --> 15:09.928
It's the big boss of the solar
system but its most deceptive

15:10.030 --> 15:13.364
weapon is something
we usually think
of as our friend.

15:16.002 --> 15:18.336
Light.

15:22.042 --> 15:26.344
It's a hazard astronauts
need special protection from.

15:37.324 --> 15:40.725
JEFF: We see the
visible light from
the sun but there's

15:40.827 --> 15:44.062
also ultraviolet light.

15:44.631 --> 15:47.899
That can actually do
significant damage.

15:49.569 --> 15:54.172
JERRY: Every porthole
window has special layers,
different UV filters.

15:55.075 --> 15:58.576
On space station MIR there
was one that was not.

16:00.147 --> 16:02.580
But when I floated
over that thing,
if you sat there and

16:02.682 --> 16:05.316
had those rays of sun hit
you, in less than a minute,

16:05.418 --> 16:08.686
you'd see your skin reddened.

16:10.557 --> 16:13.958
-The power of UV light in
space means that without our

16:14.060 --> 16:18.096
gold visors our eyesight
could be damaged permanently.

16:19.533 --> 16:24.102
For almost all life
on earth facing the sun
as we do in space would

16:24.204 --> 16:26.204
ultimately be fatal.

16:36.283 --> 16:41.786
♪ ♪

16:42.856 --> 16:44.656
It's crazy, right?

16:44.758 --> 16:48.393
In space you need a
$12 million spacesuit to
protect you from the sun...

16:51.298 --> 16:55.133
whereas on the surface of
the earth just some lotion
does the job perfectly fine.

17:04.144 --> 17:09.380
♪ ♪

17:09.482 --> 17:11.816
We're quite fortunate.

17:11.918 --> 17:15.553
Only about 2% of the really
damaging ultraviolet radiation

17:15.655 --> 17:19.724
from the sun actually
gets down to the surface.

17:26.333 --> 17:30.001
If every bit got
down to earth...

17:32.472 --> 17:35.673
skin would burn in
a matter of seconds.

17:37.310 --> 17:39.677
That's just the start.

17:48.989 --> 17:53.691
UV radiation
breaks down DNA and turns
healthy cells cancerous.

17:55.762 --> 17:59.297
If we were hit by the
full force of the sun,

17:59.699 --> 18:02.033
plants would be sterilized...

18:03.136 --> 18:05.536
microscopic life
would be sterilized...

18:07.974 --> 18:11.643
life couldn't be sustained
on the surface of the earth.

18:26.693 --> 18:30.962
WILL SMITH: Ultraviolet light
is vicious so how come we're

18:31.064 --> 18:33.464
not burned to a crisp?

18:34.901 --> 18:38.136
The answer is high above us.

18:40.307 --> 18:43.808
The sun slings deadly
UV light at us...

18:45.145 --> 18:48.246
but most of it is stopped in
its tracks by a thin blanket

18:48.348 --> 18:52.183
of molecules that we
call the ozone layer.

18:56.056 --> 19:01.092
The ozone layer is
our second shield in
the sky but it's fragile,

19:02.162 --> 19:04.862
extremely fragile.

19:09.102 --> 19:12.470
30 years ago, we discovered
manmade chemicals had punched

19:12.572 --> 19:16.274
a hole in the ozone layer.

19:19.379 --> 19:21.612
Is that hole here to stay?

19:21.715 --> 19:24.816
Waiting around to kill us?

19:24.918 --> 19:28.853
Today we're trying
hard to find out.

19:37.597 --> 19:43.901
♪ ♪

19:52.712 --> 19:59.083
♪ ♪

20:00.620 --> 20:06.290
Morgan Sandercock is about
to test an experimental plane
perfect for sampling ozone.

20:07.127 --> 20:09.727
<i>MAN (over radio):</i>
<i>Go ahead, go,</i>
<i>pressurizing.</i>

20:09.829 --> 20:13.498
<i>We think we can go as</i>
<i>high as 90,000 feet.</i>
<i>Jim, you're ready to go.</i>

20:13.600 --> 20:15.199
<i>JIM (over radio): I'm ready.</i>

20:15.301 --> 20:17.035
MORGAN: That's the
big boy territory.

20:17.137 --> 20:21.139
That's where things can
wrong very, very quickly.

20:21.241 --> 20:26.210
If we lose cabin pressure,
then the pilots could very

20:26.312 --> 20:30.748
easily pass out and we don't
have any automatic systems to

20:30.850 --> 20:32.550
recover from that.

20:32.652 --> 20:34.485
<i>WOMAN (over radio):</i>
<i>Getting ready to roll.</i>

20:34.587 --> 20:37.755
WILL SMITH: Now a
glider might sound like a
dangerous choice so high up,

20:37.857 --> 20:42.427
but gliders don't
have engines which means
they can't pollute

20:42.529 --> 20:44.495
the team's samples.

20:44.597 --> 20:46.898
<i>MAN (over radio): Got</i>
<i>a firm count, dolly off.</i>

20:47.000 --> 20:49.333
<i>WOMAN (over radio):</i>
<i>Count, dolly is off,</i>
<i>wing wheel is off.</i>

20:49.436 --> 20:51.869
<i>MAN (over radio):</i>
<i>Okay, rolling at 11:32.</i>

20:51.971 --> 20:55.173
-11:32, written down, if
you can get us the time.

20:55.942 --> 20:58.109
<i>MAN (over radio): Airborne.</i>

21:13.493 --> 21:19.664
♪ ♪

21:26.406 --> 21:30.141
WILL SMITH: The Perlan glider
uses air rising over the
southern Andes

21:30.243 --> 21:33.978
to reach
extraordinary heights.

21:35.915 --> 21:41.419
-Air speed, 70 knots.
Looking beautiful,
(inaudible).

21:43.089 --> 21:44.922
<i>MAN (over radio):</i>
<i>Traffic, yeah.</i>

21:53.766 --> 21:57.135
WILL SMITH: 52,000 feet up
makes this the highest glider

21:57.237 --> 22:02.507
flight ever but you've gotta
get this high to get a great
picture of the ozone layer.

22:03.843 --> 22:06.844
The good news is that thanks
to a global ban on ozone

22:06.946 --> 22:10.848
harming chemicals, it looks
like the hole is healing up.

22:12.919 --> 22:16.587
Our shield is regenerating.

22:30.937 --> 22:33.871
MIKE: Our planet is not
an inanimate object.

22:33.973 --> 22:36.140
It's a living thing
and it can heal itself.

22:40.947 --> 22:44.282
JERRY: When we discovered
the hole in the ozone layer,

22:44.384 --> 22:47.985
mankind did come
together on that one and
we banned those substances.

22:52.392 --> 22:58.162
-You look down and
you see this fragile
planet which supports life

22:59.098 --> 23:02.366
on its surface in the
face of the incredible

23:02.468 --> 23:06.037
hostility and so you
become much more sensitive,

23:06.139 --> 23:09.240
I think, to the
need to protect it.

23:14.447 --> 23:18.583
WILL SMITH: Any way
you look at it, the
ozone layer is pretty special.

23:23.122 --> 23:27.692
This shield has looked
after us for millions of years,

23:28.494 --> 23:32.763
even before mankind
came down from the trees,
even before the

23:32.865 --> 23:36.467
dinosaurs walked the earth.

23:37.370 --> 23:41.806
Without the ozone layer
there would be no human race.

23:43.142 --> 23:46.377
Life on earth would be
trapped under water.

23:55.355 --> 23:58.156
WILL SMITH: In Earth's battle
with the sun, the sun has

23:58.258 --> 24:00.892
often had the upper hand.

24:03.530 --> 24:06.998
Today the ozone
layer protects us from
UV but once upon a time,

24:08.034 --> 24:09.868
it wasn't there.

24:12.005 --> 24:15.373
The only safe place for
life was under the waves.

24:18.745 --> 24:21.646
Life would probably
still be down there if
it wasn't for something

24:21.748 --> 24:26.417
new that emerged
nearly three billion
years ago and found a way

24:26.520 --> 24:30.889
to use sunlight
to its advantage.

24:40.267 --> 24:45.303
♪ ♪

24:45.572 --> 24:50.441
JEFF: Billions of years
ago as ancient organisms first
harnessed the energy of the sun,

24:51.912 --> 24:55.947
they began
producing a waste product.

24:56.216 --> 24:58.716
Oxygen.

25:02.088 --> 25:06.991
At first it was just
a few individuals, but
thousands became millions.

25:09.830 --> 25:12.497
Millions became trillions.

25:12.599 --> 25:15.667
All bubbling up oxygen.

25:17.804 --> 25:20.972
When oxygen gas rises high
into the atmosphere something

25:21.074 --> 25:24.008
very special happens to it.

25:25.178 --> 25:28.947
It transforms into
protective ozone.

25:32.085 --> 25:36.554
Under the shelter of this
ozone layer, first microbes

25:36.656 --> 25:40.959
then fungi and plants
migrated out of the water.

25:44.364 --> 25:48.233
And this meant even more
oxygen was being produced,

25:48.335 --> 25:53.471
further strengthening
our shield against
the sun's UV light.

25:55.442 --> 25:58.843
And this would help make
possible one of our planet's

25:58.945 --> 26:02.113
most defining moments.

26:11.191 --> 26:17.328
♪ ♪

26:23.036 --> 26:27.071
Protected by a thicker
ozone layer than ever before,

26:27.173 --> 26:31.509
a whole new world of
possibilities opened
up for life on earth.

26:40.754 --> 26:46.925
♪ ♪

26:54.601 --> 26:58.469
We think it was about 400
million years ago when simple

26:58.571 --> 27:03.408
vertebrates first took their
tentative steps onto dry land.

27:08.114 --> 27:12.517
It's probable that these
early animals were moving
around using something that

27:12.619 --> 27:15.353
was still pretty
much like the fins
that they used to get

27:15.455 --> 27:18.222
around in the water.

27:23.964 --> 27:28.533
With that one small step
from water to dry land...

27:33.974 --> 27:38.543
life on earth changed forever.

27:41.147 --> 27:45.917
That was one small step
for animal kind and one
giant leap for life on earth.

27:55.929 --> 27:58.363
♪ ♪

27:58.465 --> 28:02.166
WILL SMITH: Life spilled
out of the water in a
billion different ways

28:02.268 --> 28:05.169
taking on a host of forms.

28:06.573 --> 28:10.174
All because of that special
layer of oxygen up in the sky.

28:13.680 --> 28:17.315
Right, so that's two shields
that our planet gives us.

28:18.284 --> 28:21.252
But the sun has
a final weapon.

28:21.521 --> 28:23.321
Heat.

28:23.423 --> 28:27.091
It's pumping out
millions of degrees of
powerful burn and that

28:27.193 --> 28:31.329
powerful burn is intensified
by an ally down here on earth,

28:32.465 --> 28:35.533
one feared by
